snippet.textDisplay:
I've always found the idea of "measurement" within quantum mechanics (i.e. opening the box) to be infuriating. Why would measuring an effect (wave) result in an event (particle)? How does the wave-particle "know" it's been observed?


This rather brilliantly answers that question by stating the wave doesn't know it's been observed. To borrow from Relativity: The wave's state is objective; the particle's is subjective.


Thus, what we "perceive" to be a wave collapsing into a particle is, in fact, merely a point upon/within the wave. The rest of the wave is conserved. It merely continues on to form other "realities" where the remaining points are perceived.


This then leads to the improved descriptor of "branching realities" rather than "parallel universes." However, the idea of branching remains black-white (binary) rather than greyscale. So then, "probable" is rendered irrelevant as it is an "absolute" that all possible events will happen. What we perceive as probability is at which point upon the wave will an event occur? But, this is moot as all events will occur—it's just that the event you observe is the branch you have travelled upon.


This then begs the question: can branches re-entangle? If two people observe different events on one wave, then observe the same event upon a different wave, do their realities recombine? On the macro scale, of course, would you notice?


The impulse is to say "yes." In your reality, you had breakfast at 9:00 AM, while in mine, you had breakfast at 9:05 AM. Then we met for lunch at 12:00 PM and compared notes. Easily discernible. But, what if, in my reality, you had breakfast at 9:00:30 AM? Would that be so easily discerned? We then continue along our parallel realities until we both sit down for lunch at exactly 12:00 PM—thus re-entangling our realities.

snippet.textDisplay:
The problem of Many Worlds is that it doesn't give an account for the accuracy of probability predictions. If upon opening the box containing Schroedinger's cat, the cat will be alive and dead (in separate branches of the wave function) then what does probability mean if all branches happen with probability 100%? To make this explicit, imagine that the radioactive atom used in the experiment has a half-life of 1 hour. Instead of waiting 1 hour for the probability of the cat being dead to be 50%, wait 2 hours so that the probability of the cat being dead is 75%. If upon opening the box, the cat is both alive and dead with certainty, where did the 75% probability come from (or where did it go)? I know the 75% probability of dead cat is true because I can repeat the experiment multiple times and find that the cat is dead (is this comment morbid enough yet?) about 75% of the time. The Measurement Postulate of quantum mechanics--probability = |wavefunction|^2--is empirically verifiable. To toss it out is unjustified. A scientific theory must connect to humans' experiences of the world for them to be useful and measurement is the human experience. Again, the probabilities that come out of the inconvenient Measurement Postulate are empirically verified, so it cannot be discarded.


I make no claim to know what the proper interpretation of quantum mechanics is, but Many Worlds in its current form is by no means the obviously correct choice.

I make no claim to know what the proper interpretation of quantum mechanics is, but Many Worlds in its current form is by no means the obviously correct choice.

snippet.textDisplay:
Nice video. It doesn't mention the conflict about the 'interpretation' differences and errs specifically in expressing the entangled particle's as linked by rational means that is denied in the Copenhagen interpretation except by Sean's mentioning of the statistical interpretations at the end that relates to the topic.


That error (or incomplete represention) is at the 7:15 point where he assumes the wave function is tied to the entangled particles as a type of 'hidden factor' [not literally said but expressed.] The Copenhagen interpretation says there is no linked factor such that observing one instantanously affects the other. This was supposedly 'proven' by using Bell's Theorem modeling the challenge by the EPR paper. The type of logic using that math/logic with experiment seems to prove the reality but the error is identical in form to the Monty Hall Problem, something that I've argued AND linked as related. The different interpretations of statistics is part of the problem but also, the 2/3 solution of that has a 'hidden' factor (a cheat that makes that solution true by how the presentation to the problem is made). In other words, if the real experiment proves the 2/3 imbalance (rather than a 1/2 probability), this actually require a hidden factor contradicting Copenhagen, not actually supporting it. And this is where Sean's point about the interpretation of statistics itself plays a role in the confusion.

The radiation detector is measuring the decay, which is a macroscopic event.

There is a fundamental difference between the quantum wave function when it is not collapsed, and not knowing about it the result of a collapse.

snippet.textDisplay:
The way I see it is that parallel universes are just possibilities (therefore, hypothetical universes), not separate child universes that split from one parent and are running the result of each possibility.
You roll a dice with the eyes closed. Your "wave formula" determines that the dice is a set of six possible situations (=universes) with the same probability. When you open your eyes and measure the result, you don't enter one of the six universes but you just find out what happened on The Universe. The parallel universes are different possibilities and only one occurs at a time.

snippet.textDisplay: The cat can’t be both alive and dead. Limited human intelligence [and a desire of human intelligence to have no limit] will tell you that the cat is “both alive and dead” but this is an absurdity, no matter what perspective it comes from. In reality no one knows whether the cat is alive or dead until they open the box, until then the cat can be alive or dead or on the brink of death, but nothing can make the cat both. It’s like flipping a coin onto a spring-switch and hiding the coin. No one knows if the coin is heads or tails, no one can know if it is heads or tails without possibly changing what it already is, but it cannot be both...
